{
  "doc_id": "31500",
  "text": "Molecular chaperones recognize unfolded or partially folded proteins and promote acquisition of the functional native state [CITATION_1] . Nascent polypeptides or damaged proteins are especially at risk and interaction with a chaperone such as Heat shock protein 70 (Hsp70) stabilizes these substrates, preventing aggregation and allowing progress along a productive folding trajectory. Severely damaged proteins incapable of achieving a stable conformation are selected for triage in a process termed protein quality control, wherein Hsp70 and accessory proteins such as the mammalian E3 ubiquitin ligase Chip target the substrate for degradation via the ubiquitin-proteasome system [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Factors influencing the decision to fold or degrade substrate proteins are poorly understood, but include cochaperones that regulate substrate association with Hsp70 [CITATION_4] .",
